  "prompt": "How can I calculate the molar absorptivity of a wavelength?",
  "response": "To calculate the molar absorptivity (\u03b5), you'll need to follow these steps:\n\n1. Use the Beer-Lambert Law: A = \u03b5 * c * l\n   Where:\n   A = Absorbance\n   \u03b5 = Molar absorptivity (L mol\u207b\u00b9 cm\u207b\u00b9)\n   c = Concentration of the solution (mol L\u207b\u00b9)\n   l = Path length of the sample (cm)\n\n2. Rearrange the equation to solve for \u03b5:\n   \u03b5 = A / (c * l)\n\n3. Experimental procedure:\n   - Measure the absorbance (A) at a specific wavelength\n   - Know the concentration (c) of the solution\n   - Measure the path length (l) of the sample cell\n\n4. Example calculation:\n   If A = 0.5\n   c = 0.1 mol/L\n   l = 1 cm\n   \n   \u03b5 = 0.5 / (0.1 * 1) = 5 L mol\u207b\u00b9 cm\u207b\u00b9\n\n5. Repeat measurements at different concentrations to ensure accuracy\n\nEnsure precise measurements and use standard spectrophotometric techniques.",
